Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip (palms facing forward). Keep your elbows close to your torso and your back straight. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, squeezing your biceps at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position with control.[1][2][3][4][5]

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip (palms facing each other). Keep your elbows close to your torso and your back straight. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, maintaining the neutral grip throughout the movement. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Place your left knee and left hand on a flat bench, keeping your back parallel to the floor. Hold a dumbbell in your right hand with your arm extended towards the floor. Pull the dumbbell up towards your chest, squeezing your back muscles. Keep your elbow close to your body. Slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching to the other.

Lie on a flat bench with your feet firmly on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand at chest level with your palms facing forward. Press the dumbbells up until your arms are fully extended but not locked. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position in a controlled manner.

Sit on a bench with back support or stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Hold a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height with your palms facing forward and elbows bent at a 90-degree angle. Press the dumbbells overhead until your arms are fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie on a flat bench with your feet on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand directly above your chest with a slight bend in your elbows and your palms facing each other. Slowly lower the dumbbells out to your sides in a wide arc, keeping the slight bend in your elbows. Lower the weights until you feel a stretch in your chest, then use your chest muscles to bring the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie on a flat bench holding a dumbbell in each hand directly above your chest with a neutral grip (palms facing each other). Keeping your upper arms stationary, bend at the elbows to lower the dumbbells towards your head. Lower the weights until your elbows are at a 90-degree angle. Extend your arms to press the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand in front of your thighs with an overhand grip (palms facing your body). Keeping your arms straight with a slight bend in the elbows, raise the dumbbells in front of you until they are at shoulder height. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Sit on a bench with back support, holding one dumbbell with both hands overhead. Your hands should be interlocked around the handle. Lower the dumbbell behind your head by bending at the elbows. Keep your upper arms stationary. Extend your arms to press the dumbbell back to the starting position.

Set an incline bench to a 30-45 degree angle. Lie on the bench with your feet firmly on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand at chest level with your palms facing forward. Press the dumbbells up until your arms are fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet together, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides. Step forward with your right leg and lower your hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Your front knee should be directly above your ankle, and your back knee should be hovering just off the floor. Push off your right foot to return to the starting position. Repeat on the other side.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Hinge at your hips so your torso is nearly parallel to the floor, keeping your back straight. Let the dumbbells hang in front of you with your palms facing each other. Raise the dumbbells out to your sides, keeping a slight bend in your elbows and squeezing your shoulder blades together. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with an overhand grip. Hinge at your hips and bend your knees slightly, keeping your back straight until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Pull the dumbbells up towards your chest, keeping your elbows close to your body. Squeeze your back muscles at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Place your left knee and left hand on a flat bench. Hold a dumbbell in your right hand with your elbow bent at a 90-degree angle and your upper arm parallel to the floor. Extend your arm straight back, squeezing your triceps. Slowly return to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand in front of your thighs. Keeping your legs relatively straight (with a slight bend in the knees), hinge at your hips and lower the dumbbells towards the floor. Keep your back straight. Lower the weights as far as your flexibility allows, then return to the starting position by squeezing your glutes and hamstrings.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides with your palms facing your body. Keeping your arms straight with a slight bend in the elbows, raise the dumbbells out to your sides until they are at shoulder height. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Sit on a bench with your feet flat on the floor, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip (palms facing forward). Keep your back straight and your elbows close to your sides. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, squeezing your biceps at the top. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides. Keeping your chest up and your back straight, lower your hips as if you are sitting in a chair. Go as low as you can comfortably, aiming for your thighs to be parallel to the floor. Push through your heels to return to the starting position.

Sit on the edge of a bench with your feet planted firmly on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in your right hand and rest your right elbow on the inside of your right thigh. Let your arm hang straight down. Curl the dumbbell up towards your shoulder, keeping your upper arm and elbow stationary. Squeeze your bicep at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides with your palms facing your body. Elevate your shoulders as high as you can, as if you are trying to touch your ears with your shoulders. Hold the contraction at the top for a moment, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Sit on a bench with back support, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height with your palms facing your body. As you press the dumbbells overhead, rotate your wrists so that your palms are facing forward at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position, reversing the wrist rotation.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height. Perform a squat, keeping your chest up and back straight. As you return to the standing position, press the dumbbells overhead until your arms are fully extended. Lower the dumbbells back to shoulder height to complete one rep.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides with your palms facing your body. Keeping your arms straight with a slight bend in the elbows, raise the dumbbells out to your sides until they are at shoulder height. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Sit on an incline bench set to a 45-60 degree angle, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your arms hanging straight down and your palms facing forward. Keeping your upper arms stationary, curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand on your right leg, holding a dumbbell in your right hand. Keeping your right leg slightly bent, hinge at your hips and lower the dumbbell towards the floor. Extend your left leg straight back behind you for balance. Lower the weight as far as you can while maintaining a flat back, then return to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand in front of your thighs with an overhand grip. Pull the dumbbells straight up towards your chin, leading with your elbows. Keep the weights close to your body. Lower the dumbbells back to the starting position in a controlled manner.

Stand or sit, holding one dumbbell with your right hand directly overhead. Support your right elbow with your left hand. Lower the dumbbell behind your head by bending at the elbow. Extend your arm to press the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip. Curl the right dumbbell up and across your body towards your left shoulder. Slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Repeat with the left dumbbell, curling it towards your right shoulder.

Stand with your feet wider than shoulder-width apart, with your toes pointed out at a 45-degree angle. Hold one dumbbell with both hands in front of your chest. Lower your hips down and back, keeping your chest up and your back straight. Push through your heels to return to the starting position.

Lie face down on an incline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing each other. Raise the dumbbells out to your sides, keeping a slight bend in your elbows and squeezing your shoulder blades together. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie on an incline bench with your feet on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand directly above your chest with a slight bend in your elbows and your palms facing each other. Slowly lower the dumbbells out to your sides in a wide arc. Lower the weights until you feel a stretch in your chest, then use your chest muscles to bring the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip. Perform a bicep curl. At the top of the curl, rotate your wrists and press the dumbbells overhead into a shoulder press. Reverse the movement to return to the starting position.

Stand or sit, holding one dumbbell with both hands overhead. Lower the dumbbell behind your head by bending at the elbows. Keep your upper arms stationary. Extend your arms to press the dumbbell back to the starting position.

Lie on a flat bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip, pressed together over your chest. Lower the dumbbells to your chest, keeping them pressed together. Press the dumbbells back up to the starting position.

Lie on the floor with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your elbows resting on the floor at a 45-degree angle from your body. Press the dumbbells up until your arms are fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie face down on an incline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing each other. Pull the dumbbells up towards your chest, squeezing your back muscles. Keep your elbows close to your body. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand in front of a bench or step, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Step up onto the bench with your right foot, pressing through your heel to straighten your leg. Bring your left foot up to meet your right foot. Step back down with your right foot, followed by your left foot. Repeat, leading with the opposite leg.

Sit on an incline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip. Let your arms hang straight down. Keeping your upper arms stationary, curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height with your palms facing forward. Press the dumbbells overhead until your arms are fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in your right hand. Keeping your back straight, bend to your right side as far as you can comfortably go. Return to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand in front of your thighs. Keeping your legs straight with a slight bend in the knees, hinge at your hips and lower the dumbbells towards the floor. Keep your back straight. Lower the weights as far as your flexibility allows, then return to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Hinge at your hips and bend your knees to lower the dumbbells to your shins. Explosively extend your hips and knees while shrugging your shoulders and pulling the dumbbells up towards your shoulders. "Catch" the dumbbells at shoulder height in a squat position. Stand up to complete the lift.

Sit on the floor with your upper back against a bench and a dumbbell across your hips. Your knees should be bent and your feet flat on the floor. Drive through your heels to lift your hips until your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees. Squeeze your glutes at the top, then slowly lower your hips back to the starting position.

Stand a few feet in front of a bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Place the top of your right foot on the bench behind you. Lower your hips until your left thigh is parallel to the floor. Push through your left heel to return to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding one dumbbell vertically in front of your chest with both hands. Lower your hips down and back, keeping your chest up and your back straight. Push through your heels to return to the starting position.

Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Place a dumbbell across your hips. Drive through your heels to lift your hips until your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees. Squeeze your glutes at the top, then slowly lower your hips back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip, with your arms wider than your shoulders. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, keeping your elbows flared out. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Perform a lateral raise by lifting the dumbbells out to your sides. At the top of the movement, bring the dumbbells together in front of you. Lower the dumbbells to the starting position.

Lie on a flat bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand at chest level. Press the right dumbbell up until your arm is fully extended. As you lower the right dumbbell, press the left dumbbell up. Continue alternating sides.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip. Curl the dumbbells up. At the top of the curl, rotate your wrists so your palms are facing down (pronated grip). Slowly lower the dumbbells with the pronated grip. At the bottom, rotate your wrists back to a supinated grip.

Sit on the edge of a bench, leaning forward with your chest close to your knees. Hold a dumbbell in each hand with your palms facing each other. Raise the dumbbells out to your sides, keeping a slight bend in your elbows and squeezing your shoulder blades together. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie on an incline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip, pressed together over your chest. Lower the dumbbells to your chest, keeping them pressed together. Press the dumbbells back up to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding the top of a dumbbell with both hands, palms up. Curl the dumbbell up towards your chest, keeping your elbows tucked in. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position.

Sit on a bench and rest your forearms on your thighs, with your wrists hanging off your knees and your palms facing up. Hold a dumbbell in each hand. Curl your wrists up as far as you can. Slowly lower your wrists back to the starting position.
Lie on a decline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand at chest level. Press the dumbbells up until your arms are fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet wider than shoulder-width apart, with your toes pointed out at a 45-degree angle. Hold one dumbbell vertically in front of your chest with both hands. Lower your hips down and back, keeping your chest up and your back straight. Push through your heels to return to the starting position.
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your arms extended out to your sides at shoulder height. Hold this position for the desired amount of time.

Sit on a bench and rest your forearms on your thighs, with your wrists hanging off your knees and your palms facing down. Hold a dumbbell in each hand. Extend your wrists up as far as you can. Slowly lower your wrists back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a pronated grip (palms facing down). Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, keeping your elbows close to your sides. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your sides. With a slight bend in your elbows, raise the dumbbells in a wide arc in front of you until they meet overhead. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position in the same wide arc.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip. As you curl the dumbbells up, externally rotate your shoulders so that your palms are facing out at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position, reversing the rotation.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Hinge at your hips so your torso is nearly parallel to the floor, keeping your back straight. Let the dumbbells hang in front of you with your palms facing each other. Raise the dumbbells out to your sides, keeping a slight bend in your elbows and squeezing your shoulder blades together. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Sit at a preacher curl bench, holding a dumbbell in your right hand. Rest your right arm on the pad. Curl the dumbbell up towards your shoulder. Squeeze your bicep at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Lie face down on the floor, holding a light dumbbell in each hand with your arms extended in front of you. Simultaneously raise your arms, chest, and legs off the floor. Hold for a moment, then slowly lower back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet flat on the floor, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Raise your heels as high as you can, pausing at the top to squeeze your calf muscles. Slowly lower your heels back to the floor.

Start in a plank position with your hands on two dumbbells. Keeping your core tight and your hips level, row one dumbbell up to your chest. Lower the dumbbell back to the floor and repeat on the other side.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a supinated grip. Instead of curling the dumbbells up in an arc, "drag" them up along the front of your body by pulling your elbows back. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Lie on the floor with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Hold a dumbbell in your right hand with your elbow resting on the floor at a 45-degree angle from your body. Press the dumbbell up until your arm is fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Lie on a decline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand directly above your chest with a slight bend in your elbows and your palms facing each other. Slowly lower the dumbbells out to your sides in a wide arc. Lower the weights until you feel a stretch in your chest, then use your chest muscles to bring the dumbbells back to the starting position.
Start on all fours with your hands on two dumbbells. Extend your right arm and left leg straight out. Row the left dumbbell up to your chest. Lower the dumbbell and repeat on the other side.

Lie face down on an incline bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand with your arms hanging straight down. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders, keeping your upper arms stationary. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height with your palms facing your body. As you press the dumbbells overhead, rotate your wrists so that your palms are facing forward at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position, reversing the wrist rotation.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding one dumbbell with both hands overhead. Lower the dumbbell behind your head by bending at the elbows. Keep your upper arms stationary. Extend your arms to press the dumbbell back to the starting position.

Exercise: Elbows Out Bent Over Dumbbell Row
Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with an overhand grip. Hinge at your hips and bend your knees slightly, keeping your back straight until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Pull the dumbbells up towards your chest, flaring your elbows out to the sides. Squeeze your back and shoulder muscles at the top of the movement. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in your right hand at shoulder height. Press the dumbbell overhead until your arm is fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Lie on a flat bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand directly above your chest with your palms facing your feet. Lower the dumbbells towards your chest by bending at the elbows, keeping your elbows flared out. Press the dumbbells back up to the starting position.

Stand with your feet hip-width apart with a dumbbell on the floor between your feet. Squat down and grab the dumbbell with your right hand. In one explosive movement, pull the dumbbell up, keeping it close to your body. As the dumbbell passes your chest, punch your hand under the dumbbell to "catch" it overhead with your arm fully extended. Stand up to complete the lift.

Stand with your feet together, holding a dumbbell in your right hand, pressed overhead. Step forward with your left leg and lower your hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Push off your left foot to return to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Exercise: Dumbbell Lateral Raise To Front Raise
Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Perform a lateral raise by lifting the dumbbells out to your sides. At the top of the movement, bring the dumbbells together in front of you. Lower the dumbbells to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at your shoulders. Keeping your back straight and your legs relatively straight, hinge at your hips and lower your torso until it is parallel to the floor. Return to the starting position by squeezing your glutes and hamstrings.

Sit at a preacher curl bench, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Rest your arms on the pad. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders. Squeeze your biceps at the top, then slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet together, holding a dumbbell in each hand, pressed overhead. Step forward with your right leg and lower your hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Push off your right foot to return to the starting position.
Sit on a bench with a dumbbell resting on each knee. Raise your heels as high as you can, pausing at the top to squeeze your calf muscles. Slowly lower your heels back to the floor.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand in front of your thighs with a supinated grip (palms facing forward). Keeping your arms straight with a slight bend in the elbows, raise the dumbbells in front of you until they are at shoulder height. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Stand with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Step your right leg back and behind your left leg, as if you are doing a curtsy. Lower your hips until your left thigh is parallel to the floor. Push off your right foot to return to the starting position. Repeat on the other side.

Exercise: Dumbbell Standing Hammer Curl To Front Press
Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip. Perform a hammer curl. At the top of the curl, press the dumbbells forward until your arms are fully extended. Reverse the movement to return to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand with a neutral grip. Curl the dumbbells up towards your shoulders. Pause at the top of the movement for a count of two, squeezing your biceps. Slowly lower the dumbbells back to the starting position.

Exercise: Dumbbell Romanian Deadlift to Bent Over Row
Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Perform a Romanian deadlift. At the bottom of the movement, perform a bent-over row by pulling the dumbbells up to your chest. Lower the dumbbells, then return to the starting position.
Stand with your feet hip-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Perform a Romanian deadlift. As you return to the starting position, perform a shrug by elevating your shoulders.

Exercise: Standing Single Arm Dumbbell Shoulder Press
Instructions for Proper Form: Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in your right hand at shoulder height. Press the dumbbell overhead until your arm is fully extended. Slowly lower the dumbbell back to the starting position. Complete all reps on one side before switching.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, holding a dumbbell in each hand at shoulder height with your palms facing your body. Press the dumbbells forward until your arms are fully extended. Slowly return the dumbbells to the starting position.

Stand with your feet together, holding a dumbbell in each hand. Step forward with your right leg and lower your hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Instead of pushing back to the starting position, push off your left foot and step forward into the next lunge.

Lie with your upper back on a bench, with your feet on the floor. Hold one dumbbell with both hands over your chest. Lower the dumbbell behind your head in an arc. Pull the dumbbell back over your chest to the starting position.

Start in a plank position with your hands slightly wider than your shoulders. Lower your body until your chest nearly touches the floor, keeping your back straight and core engaged. Push back up to the starting position.

Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Lower your hips back and down as if you are sitting in a chair, keeping your chest up and back straight. Go as low as you can comfortably, aiming to get your thighs parallel to the floor. Push through your heels to return to the starting position.

Hold your body in a straight line from your head to your heels, supported by your forearms and toes. Keep your core tight and don't let your hips sag. Hold the position for the desired amount of time.

From a standing position, step one foot forward and lower your hips until both knees are bent at a 90-degree angle. Your front knee should be directly above your ankle, and your back knee should be hovering just off the ground. Push off your front foot to return to the starting position. Repeat on the other side.

Start in a standing position. Drop into a squat and place your hands on the floor. Kick your feet back into a plank position, then lower your chest to the floor. Push back up to a plank, then jump your feet forward to your hands. Jump up explosively from the squat position.

Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Place your hands behind your head or across your chest. Raise your upper body towards your knees, using your core muscles. Slowly lower yourself back to the starting position.
Start in a plank position. Drive your right knee towards your chest, then quickly switch and drive your left knee towards your chest. Continue alternating legs in a running motion.

Sit on the edge of a bench or chair with your hands gripping the edge next to your hips. Slide your hips forward off the bench. Lower your body by bending your elbows until they are at a 90-degree angle. Push back up to the starting position.
Stand with your feet flat on the floor. Raise your heels as high as you can, pausing at the top to squeeze your calf muscles. Slowly lower your heels back to the floor.
Stand with your back against a wall. Slide down the wall until your knees are bent at a 90-degree angle and your thighs are parallel to the floor. Hold this position for the desired amount of time.
Sit on the floor with your knees bent and feet off the floor. Lean back to engage your core. Twist your torso from side to side.
Lie on your back with your legs straight. Slowly raise your legs until they are perpendicular to the floor. Slowly lower your legs back to the starting position without letting them touch the floor.

Lie on your back with your hands behind your head and your knees bent. Bring your right elbow towards your left knee while extending your right leg. Switch sides, bringing your left elbow towards your right knee.

Start in a push-up position with your hands close together, forming a diamond shape with your thumbs and index fingers. Lower your body until your chest nearly touches your hands. Push back up to the starting position.
Start in a downward dog position with your hips high and your body forming an inverted V. Lower your head towards the floor by bending your elbows. Push back up to the starting position.

Grab a pull-up bar with an underhand grip (palms facing you). Hang with your arms fully extended. Pull your body up until your chin is over the bar. Slowly lower yourself back to the starting position.

Grab a pull-up bar with an overhand grip (palms facing away from you). Hang with your arms fully extended. Pull your body up until your chin is over the bar. Slowly lower yourself back to the starting position.

Lie on your back with your knees bent and feet flat on the floor. Extend your right leg straight out. Drive through your left heel to lift your hips off the floor. Slowly lower your hips back to the starting position.
